{
  "query": "What are the observed effects on salmon growth and flesh quality when replacing fish oil with plant-based or other animal-based oils in their diet?",
  "relevant_summary": "Studies have found mixed effects on salmon growth when replacing fish oil with plant-based oils. Three replicated studies (two controlled) in Norway found similar growth rates in salmon fed diets containing fish oil versus vegetable oil, while one study found higher growth rates in fish fed vegetable oil diets. One replicated, controlled study found salmon growth rates were both lower and higher in vegetable oil diets compared to fish oil diets, depending on family genetics.\n\nRegarding flesh quality, three replicated studies (two controlled) in Norway and Scotland found that the fatty acid profile of salmon flesh reflected the oil source within diets. A replicated, controlled study found that salmon fed vegetable oil-based diets had lower concentrations of dioxin and polychlorinated biphenyls within flesh compared to diets containing fish oil.\n\nOne study in Norway found no differences in salmon flesh quality (gaping, texture, and liquid holding capacity) between fish fed vegetable oil- and fish oil-based diets, though pigment concentration was lower in vegetable oil diets. Studies also noted some physiological differences, with one replicate Norwegian study finding that salmon fed vegetable oil diets had high liver lipid and low plasma lipoprotein compared to fish oil diets.\n\nOne controlled Canadian study on alternative animal-based lipid sources found no difference in oxygen consumption or swimming speed of Atlantic salmon fed diets containing anchovy oil or alternative lipid sources.",
  "action_ids": [
    "926",
    "922"
  ]
}

