{"summary": "Studies in Norway comparing plant-based feed alternatives for salmon show distinct effects between vegetable oils and plant proteins. For vegetable oil alternatives, three replicated studies found similar or higher growth rates in salmon fed vegetable oil diets compared to fish oil diets. However, the fatty acid profile of salmon flesh reflected the oil source, with vegetable oil diets resulting in high liver lipid and low plasma lipoprotein levels and lower concentrations of n-3 highly unsaturated fatty acids compared to fish oil diets. Salmon fed vegetable oil-based diets also had lower concentrations of dioxin and polychlorinated biphenyls in their flesh.

For plant protein alternatives, six studies found that inclusion of plant-based proteins led to decreased growth rates in salmon, with four studies showing reduced final body weights compared to fish meal-based diets. Digestibility of feed components was lower with plant proteins, and morphology of the distal intestine was altered in salmon fed plant-based protein diets. However, survival rates and appetite were not affected by plant-based protein diets.

Both alternatives maintained similar feeding efficiency levels in most studies, though some studies showed either lowered or increased feeding efficiency with plant proteins depending on the specific study conditions.", "query": "In Norway, how do different plant-based feed alternatives, such as vegetable oils versus plant proteins, affect salmon growth and body composition?", "action_ids": ["924", "926"]}

